<!--
  Chapter 15 — Statistical Reasoning
  First draft for Part IV.

  Drafted in the Chapter 1 / Chapter 14 style:
    - chapter opener as a short multi-paragraph <introduction>
    - sections decomposed into named <paragraphs> subsections
    - <definition> callouts for technical vocabulary
    - <example> callouts for worked cases
    - <exploration> field exercise at end of each section
    - "Where we're headed" subsection at end of each section
    - chapter <conclusion> for summary and key terms
    - <exercises> with <exercisegroup> sets at end of chapter

  Style conventions (carried over from Ch. 1, Ch. 14):
    <term> = first introduction of a technical term (italic + indexed)
    <em>   = emphasis only, used sparingly
    Second-person for explanation; third-person impersonal for definitions.

  Sections:
    §15.1  Measuring the Middle — mean, median, mode; when they diverge; which to use
    §15.2  Measuring Spread — range, variance, standard deviation (6-step sample SD)
    §15.3  The Normal Distribution — bell curve; empirical rule (68-95-99.7)
    §15.4  Confidence Intervals and Margin of Error — polling; 1/√n approximation
    §15.5  Diagnostic Thresholds — threshold tradeoff;
             bridge back to Bayes (Ch. 14)
    §15.6  Lying with Statistics — truncated axes; area distortion; cherry-picking

  Relationship to adjacent chapters:
    Ch. 13 introduced inductive reasoning.
    Ch. 14 covered probability, including Bayes' theorem and base rates.
    Ch. 15 (this chapter) develops the statistical tools for describing data
    and for reading statistical claims critically.
    Ch. 16 (Statistical Inference) will build on both.

  Key examples drawn from Exam 4 / SW materials:
    - Income data (SW9 analog): mean vs. median with an extreme outlier
    - Exam scores: worked SD calculation
    - Tree diameters (Exam 4 §I.3): mean 150 cm, SD 30 cm
    - Cholesterol (Exam 4 §I.4): mean 160 mg/dL, SD 50 mg/dL; sens/spec
    - Polling (Exam 4 §I.2): n = 600, 52% vs. 48%
    - Misleading graphs (Exam 4 §III): truncated axes; area/size distortion

  NOTE: main.ptx currently includes ch-inductive-reasoning in Part IV.
  This chapter should be xi:included immediately after ch-probability.ptx
  once both are ready for inclusion.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-statistical-reasoning">

  <title>Statistical Reasoning</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-statistical-reasoning-intro">
    <p>
      Chapter 14 gave us a framework for reasoning about uncertainty.
      Probability does not make the world predictable; it makes
      uncertainty precise. A probability of 0.7 for rain tomorrow is not
      a guess — it is a disciplined, quantified commitment: if forecasters
      assign 0.7 on a thousand similar days, they expect to be right about
      seven hundred of them.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter turns to the data side of the same problem. Probability
      tells us how to reason when we do not yet know what will happen.
      Statistics asks: given what we have already observed, what can we
      say about it? A doctor collects blood pressure readings from fifty
      patients and wants to know what is typical, how spread out the
      values are, and whether any of them are worryingly high. A journalist
      gets a dataset of 600 poll responses and needs to say something honest
      about what it shows. A researcher measures the trunk diameters of five
      hundred pine trees and wants to know how many fall within a particular
      range. In each case, the tools are the same: a small set of numbers
      that summarize what a larger pile of numbers says.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is the work of this chapter. We will develop tools for measuring
      a typical value, tools for measuring how spread out values are, and
      tools for using the normal distribution to connect those two numbers
      to precise probabilities. Along the way we will look at how to
      interpret the margin-of-error language that appears in virtually
      every news story that cites a poll, how to think about diagnostic
      tests (which connects back to Bayes from Chapter 14), and how to
      read statistics that are being presented to mislead.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  §15.1  Measuring the Middle                                  -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-measuring-middle">
    <title>Measuring the Middle</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A dataset is a pile of numbers. The first thing anyone wants
        from a pile of numbers is a single number that represents the whole
        pile — something you can point to and say, <q>this is what is
        typical.</q> There are three standard ways to do this, and they
        disagree with each other more often than you would expect.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-three-measures">
      <title>Three ways to find the middle</title>
      <p>
        The three standard measures of a typical value in a dataset are
        the <term>mean</term>, the <term>median</term>, and the
        <term>mode</term>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-mean">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>mean</term> of a dataset is the arithmetic average:
            the sum of all values divided by the number of values.
            To find it, add all the values and divide by how many values
            there are.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-median">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>median</term> of a dataset is the middle value when
            values are arranged in order from smallest to largest. If the
            dataset has an odd number of values, the median is the single
            middle value. If the dataset has an even number of values, the
            median is the average of the two middle values.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-mode">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>mode</term> of a dataset is the value (or values)
            that appears most often. A dataset with one mode is
            <term>unimodal</term>; one with two distinct peaks is
            <term>bimodal</term>. A dataset in which every value appears
            exactly once has no mode.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        For small, symmetric datasets, these three measures often land near
        each other — which creates the false impression that it does not
        matter which you use. It matters. The example below shows why.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-income-example">
      <title>When the three measures come apart</title>
      <p>
        Here are annual incomes, in dollars, for ten people in a workplace:
      </p>
      <p>
        Lower five: 15,000; 17,000; 23,000; 25,600; 45,000.
      </p>
      <p>
        Upper five: 54,000; 56,000; 75,000; 99,000; 1,203,000.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-income-measures">
        <title>Incomes: mean, median, and mode</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the mean, median, and mode for the ten incomes listed
            above. Then explain which measure best describes a typical
            income in this group.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <alert>Mean.</alert> The ten incomes add up to
            <m>\$1{,}612{,}600</m>. Divide that total by 10:
            the mean is <m>\$161{,}260</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Median.</alert> The data is already in order. With ten
            values, the median is the average of the 5th and 6th values.
            The average of 45,000 and 54,000 is 49,500.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Mode.</alert> No value appears more than once.
            There is no mode.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Interpretation.</alert> The mean is
            <m>\$161{,}260</m>. Nine of the ten people earn less than
            that — and seven of the ten earn less than half of it.
            The mean is inflated by the one person earning
            <m>\$1{,}203{,}000</m>. The median, at <m>\$49{,}500</m>,
            is much closer to what most people in this group actually
            earn. For describing a typical income here, the median is the
            more informative number.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      <p>
        This is not a pathological example. It is essentially how income
        distributions work across whole economies: a small number of very
        high earners pull the mean well above what most people earn. When
        income statistics appear in the news, the mean and the median are
        usually both reported — and they tell different stories. Knowing
        which story you are being told matters.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-which-measure">
      <title>Choosing the right measure</title>
      <p>
        There is no single rule for which measure to use, but there are
        useful heuristics.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use the <em>mean</em> when the data is fairly symmetric and has no
        extreme outliers. The mean uses all the values in the dataset and
        is mathematically convenient for further calculations. It is the
        right tool when the values cluster together without a long tail
        pulling it to one side.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use the <em>median</em> when the data is skewed — when there are
        extreme values on one end that pull the mean away from where most
        of the data actually sits. Income, home prices, and hospital bills
        are classic cases. The median is also more resistant to errors: a
        single misrecorded value can wildly distort the mean, but it takes
        a lot to move the median.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use the <em>mode</em> when you care about frequency, especially
        for categorical data where mean and median do not apply. The most
        common shoe size in a store's inventory, the most popular major in
        a graduating class, the most frequently assigned grade — these are
        mode questions. For numerical data, the mode is often less useful
        than the mean or median, but when a dataset is bimodal (two
        distinct clusters), that shape is itself informative: it suggests
        there may be two distinct subgroups in the data worth examining
        separately.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-middle-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        The mean, median, and mode each describe where the center of a
        distribution is. But knowing the center does not tell you how much
        the data spreads around it. Two datasets can have the same mean
        and be completely different in character. The next section
        introduces the tools for measuring that spread.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-15-1-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Find a skewed distribution</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a small dataset from a source you trust — salary data from
          a public database, enrollment figures for university departments,
          housing prices in a neighborhood, or any other numerical dataset
          with at least eight values. Calculate the mean and the median.
          If they differ by more than a few percent, investigate why: are
          there outliers? Is the distribution skewed to one side? Write a
          sentence or two explaining which measure better describes what
          is typical in your dataset, and why.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  §15.2  Measuring Spread                                      -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-measuring-spread">
    <title>Measuring Spread</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The mean tells you where the center of a distribution is. It does
        not tell you how tightly packed the data is around that center.
        Two instructors can both give courses with a class average of 75,
        but in one course every student scores between 70 and 80, while
        in the other half the class fails and half aces it. The center is
        the same; the distribution is not. To capture that difference, you
        need a measure of spread.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-range">
      <title>The range</title>
      <p>
        The simplest measure of spread is the <term>range</term>: the
        difference between the largest and smallest values in a dataset.
        A class in which scores run from 70 to 80 has a range of 10.
        A class with scores from 20 to 100 has a range of 80.
      </p>
      <p>
        The range is easy to compute, but it has a serious weakness: it
        depends entirely on the two extreme values and ignores everything
        in between. A single unusually high or low score can make a tight
        distribution look wide. For most purposes, the standard deviation
        is a better tool.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-standard-deviation">
      <title>Standard deviation</title>
      <p>
        The <term>standard deviation</term> measures, roughly speaking,
        how far each value in the dataset is from the mean, on average. A
        small standard deviation means the values cluster close to the
        mean; a large one means they spread out.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-variance-sd">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>variance</term> of a dataset is based on the squared
            distances between each value and the mean. The
            <term>standard deviation</term> is the square root of the
            variance, which brings the result back into the original units
            of measurement.
          </p>
          <p>
            Spreadsheets handle this calculation automatically. The point
            here is to understand what the number means: how tightly the
            values cluster around the mean.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        The variance is the average of the squared deviations from the
        mean. We square the deviations so that negative and positive
        deviations do not cancel each other out. The standard deviation
        brings the result back to the original units by taking the square
        root, which is why it is the more useful of the two numbers: a
        standard deviation of 10 points in a dataset of exam scores means
        something, while a variance of 100 (square exam-points) is harder
        to interpret.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-sd-six-steps">
      <title>Computing the standard deviation: a six-step procedure</title>
      <p>
        To compute the sample standard deviation by hand, follow these
        steps:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Calculate the mean.</p></li>
        <li><p>For each value, find how far it is from the mean.</p></li>
        <li><p>Square each of those differences.</p></li>
        <li><p>Add up all the squared differences.</p></li>
        <li><p>Divide by one less than the number of values. This gives
        the variance.</p></li>
        <li><p>Take the square root. This gives the standard deviation.</p></li>
      </ol>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-sd-calculation">
        <title>Computing a standard deviation: exam scores</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Five students scored 60, 70, 75, 80, and 90 on an exam.
            Find the sample standard deviation.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <alert>Step 1. Mean:</alert>
            the scores add up to 375. Divide by 5, and the mean is 75.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Steps 2 and 3. Deviations and squared deviations:</alert>
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><p>For 60: deviation -15; squared deviation 225.</p></li>
            <li><p>For 70: deviation -5; squared deviation 25.</p></li>
            <li><p>For 75: deviation 0; squared deviation 0.</p></li>
            <li><p>For 80: deviation 5; squared deviation 25.</p></li>
            <li><p>For 90: deviation 15; squared deviation 225.</p></li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <alert>Step 4. Sum of squared deviations:</alert>
            225 + 25 + 0 + 25 + 225 = 500.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Step 5. Variance:</alert>
            Divide 500 by 4, since this is sample data. The variance is
            125.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Step 6. Standard deviation:</alert>
            The square root of 125 is about 11.18.
          </p>
          <p>
            The standard deviation is approximately 11.18 points. A
            typical student in this group scored about 11 points above
            or below the mean of 75.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      <p>
        A note on computing: spreadsheets do this in a single function.
        In Excel or Google Sheets, <c>=STDEV.S()</c> computes the sample
        standard deviation, and <c>=STDEV.P()</c> computes the population
        standard deviation. For datasets larger than a handful of values,
        use a spreadsheet. The six-step procedure exists so that you
        understand what the function is doing, not so that you do it by
        hand for a hundred-item dataset.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-interpreting-sd">
      <title>Interpreting the standard deviation</title>
      <p>
        The standard deviation is useful not just as a number but as a
        unit of measurement within a dataset. Once you know the mean and
        the standard deviation, you can describe any value by how many
        standard deviations it sits above or below the mean. A score two
        standard deviations above the mean is high; two below is low; one
        on either side of the mean is comfortably in the middle of the
        pack. Whether those distances matter depends on what the data
        represents — but the comparisons work across very different
        datasets, regardless of what the original units are.
      </p>
      <p>
        The next section formalizes this idea with the normal distribution,
        which gives precise probabilities for how many values fall within
        1, 2, and 3 standard deviations of the mean.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-spread-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        We have measured the center of a distribution and its spread.
        The next step is to understand what those two numbers imply about
        the shape of the distribution — in particular, the bell-shaped
        pattern that shows up often enough to have its own name and its
        own set of rules.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-15-2-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Same mean, different spread</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Construct two small datasets — five values each — that have
          exactly the same mean but noticeably different standard
          deviations. Compute the standard deviation for each using the
          six-step procedure. Then write a sentence explaining what a
          reader would miss about each dataset if they were given only
          the mean.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  §15.3  The Normal Distribution                               -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-normal-distribution">
    <title>The Normal Distribution</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Take a large number of measurements of something that results from
        many small, independent influences — the heights of adults in a
        city, the diameters of machine-turned bolts from a factory, the
        number of points a basketball player scores per game across a long
        season — and the resulting distribution tends to take a
        characteristic shape: a bell curve, symmetric, with values
        clustering near the mean and thinning out in both directions. This
        shape is the <term>normal distribution</term>, and it appears
        frequently enough that it is worth studying on its own terms.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-bell-curve">
      <title>What the bell curve is, and what it isn't</title>
      <p>
        The normal distribution is not a law of nature. It is a
        mathematical model that fits certain kinds of data well — and a
        poor model for others. Data is approximately normally distributed
        when values cluster symmetrically around the mean, with
        progressively smaller proportions of values at greater and greater
        distances from the center. Income, as we saw in §15.1, is
        skewed right: a long tail on the high end pulls the mean above
        the median, and the distribution is anything but bell-shaped.
        The distribution of people's heights is approximately normal;
        the distribution of their net worths emphatically is not.
      </p>
      <p>
        When data is approximately normally distributed, the mean and
        standard deviation together describe the entire distribution —
        not just the center and the typical spread, but the full shape.
        That is the payoff: two numbers tell you almost everything.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-normal-distribution">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A dataset is said to be <term>normally distributed</term>
            when its values cluster symmetrically around the mean, with
            the frequency of values decreasing smoothly as they move
            farther from the mean in either direction. When graphed, the
            distribution takes the characteristic bell shape.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-empirical-rule">
      <title>The empirical rule</title>
      <p>
        For any approximately normal distribution, the following
        relationships hold with good approximation:
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-empirical-rule">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>empirical rule</term> (also called the
            <term>68-95-99.7 rule</term>) states that in any
            approximately normal distribution:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>approximately 68% of values fall within
              1 standard deviation of the mean;</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>approximately 95% of values fall within
              2 standard deviations of the mean;</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>approximately 99.7% of values fall within
              3 standard deviations of the mean.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        These percentages are approximations — the normal distribution
        is a continuous mathematical object, and real data is never
        perfectly normal — but they are close enough to be genuinely
        useful across a wide range of practical calculations.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-tree-diameters">
        <title>Pine tree trunk diameters</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A certain variety of pine tree has a mean trunk diameter of
            150 cm and a standard deviation of 30 cm. The diameters are
            approximately normally distributed. A forest contains 500 of
            these trees. Approximately how many trees have a diameter
            between 120 cm and 180 cm?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The range 120 to 180 cm spans exactly one standard deviation on
            either side of the mean:
            <m>150 - 30 = 120</m> and <m>150 + 30 = 180</m>.
            By the empirical rule, approximately 68% of values in a
            normal distribution fall within one standard deviation of
            the mean. So approximately 68% of the 500 trees fall in
            this range:
            <me>500 \times 0.682 \approx 341 \text{ trees.}</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-cholesterol">
        <title>Cholesterol levels</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Serum cholesterol levels in a reference healthy population
            are approximately normally distributed with a mean of
            160 mg/dL and a standard deviation of 50 mg/dL. What range
            of cholesterol values falls within two standard deviations
            of the mean, and approximately what percentage of the
            population falls in this range?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Two standard deviations above the mean:
            <m>160 + 2(50) = 260</m> mg/dL.
          </p>
          <p>
            Two standard deviations below the mean:
            <m>160 - 2(50) = 60</m> mg/dL.
          </p>
          <p>
            By the empirical rule, approximately 95% of values in a
            normal distribution fall within 2 standard deviations of
            the mean. So approximately 95% of the reference population
            has cholesterol between 60 and 260 mg/dL.
          </p>
          <p>
            We return to this example in <xref
            ref="sec-ch15-sensitivity-specificity"/>, where it
            illustrates how moving the boundary for what counts as
            <q>abnormal</q> affects a test's sensitivity and
            specificity.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-normal-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        The empirical rule tells us what proportion of a normal
        distribution falls within 1, 2, or 3 standard deviations of the
        mean. This is useful for describing a population. A related
        question — and one that comes up every time a poll is reported —
        is how confident we should be that a sample's findings reflect the
        population it was drawn from. That is the subject of the next
        section.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-15-3-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Apply the empirical rule</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a dataset or a news report that gives both a mean and a
          standard deviation for some real-world measurement — test scores,
          heights, reaction times, prices, anything with an approximately
          normal distribution. Use the empirical rule to calculate what
          range of values should contain the middle 95% of the
          distribution. Then check whether the source provides any
          information that lets you assess whether this is approximately
          right. Report what you found in a short paragraph.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  §15.4  Confidence Intervals and Margin of Error             -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-confidence-intervals">
    <title>Confidence Intervals and Margin of Error</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Almost every poll you read reports a margin of error. Almost no
        one stops to ask what that phrase actually means. This section
        explains it. The basic idea is not complicated, but it is precise
        — and getting it slightly wrong is the source of a remarkable
        number of bad arguments.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-why-intervals">
      <title>Why a single number is not enough</title>
      <p>
        A poll contacts 600 randomly chosen voters and asks which
        candidate they support. Fifty-two percent say Candidate A;
        48 percent say Candidate B. A news anchor announces:
        <q>Candidate A leads by four points.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        This is misleading — not because the numbers are wrong, but
        because a sample of 600 is not the entire population. Sampling
        is inherently uncertain: a different random sample of 600 people
        drawn on the same day would likely produce slightly different
        numbers. The question is how much different, and that question
        has a precise answer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Statisticians handle this uncertainty by reporting not a single
        number but an interval — a range of values consistent with what
        the sample found. That interval, combined with a stated confidence
        level, is a <term>confidence interval</term>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-confidence-interval">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>confidence interval</term> is a range of values
            computed from a sample. It is reported at a specified
            <term>confidence level</term> — typically 95% — which means
            that if the same sampling and calculation procedure were
            repeated many times, approximately 95% of the resulting
            intervals would contain the true population value.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-margin-of-error">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>margin of error</term> of a confidence interval
            is half its width — the amount added to and subtracted from
            the sample estimate to form the interval. A result of
            <q>52%, plus or minus 4%</q> means the confidence interval runs from
            48% to 56%, with a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-moe-formula">
      <title>A rule of thumb for margin of error</title>
      <p>
        The practical lesson is simple: bigger random samples have smaller
        margins of error, but the improvement slows down. Doubling a
        sample does not cut the margin of error in half. You get a
        better estimate, but each improvement costs more.
      </p>
      <p>
        For public-opinion polling at the 95% confidence level, the
        following approximations are close enough for this course:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>400 people: about plus or minus 4.9%.</p></li>
        <li><p>500 people: about plus or minus 4.4%.</p></li>
        <li><p>600 people: about plus or minus 4.1%.</p></li>
        <li><p>1,000 people: about plus or minus 3.1%.</p></li>
        <li><p>1,500 people: about plus or minus 2.5%.</p></li>
        <li><p>2,000 people: about plus or minus 2.2%.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These figures come from a square-root approximation, but you do not
        need to do that calculation every time.
        The point is to read the margin of error correctly and to notice
        when a headline treats an uncertain estimate as if it were exact.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-polling-interval">
        <title>Interpreting a poll</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A random sample of 600 voters finds that 52% support
            Candidate A and 48% support Candidate B. A news anchor says,
            <q>Candidate A will almost certainly win.</q> Is this claim
            supported by the data?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            A random sample of 600 gives a margin of error of about
            plus or minus 4 percentage points at the 95% confidence level.
          </p>
          <p>
            So the confidence interval for Candidate A's true support is
            52%, plus or minus 4 percentage points, which runs from 48%
            to 56%. The confidence interval for Candidate B's support is
            48%, plus or minus 4 percentage points, which runs from 44%
            to 52%.
          </p>
          <p>
            These intervals overlap. It is consistent with the data — at
            the 95% confidence level — that Candidate B is actually ahead.
            The anchor's claim overstates what the poll supports. A more
            accurate headline: <q>The race is within the margin of
            error.</q>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-what-ci-means">
      <title>What a confidence interval means — and what it doesn't</title>
      <p>
        A 95% confidence interval is consistently misinterpreted, in
        both news coverage and everyday conversation. Here is what it
        means and two things it does not mean.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>What it means.</alert> If we repeatedly drew random
        samples of the same size and computed a confidence interval from
        each, approximately 95% of those intervals would contain the true
        population value. The 95% describes the <em>procedure</em> over
        many repetitions, not any particular interval.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>What it does not mean (1).</alert> It does not mean there
        is a 95% probability that the true value lies in this specific
        interval. The true value is a fixed number — it either is or is
        not in the interval. The probability language applies to the
        long-run behavior of the method.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>What it does not mean (2).</alert> It is not a guarantee.
        Five percent of 95% confidence intervals, by definition, do not
        contain the true population value. If a study runs twenty
        significance tests all at the 95% confidence level, we should
        expect roughly one to give a misleading result even when
        everything is done correctly. This is part of why replication
        matters in science and why single studies should be interpreted
        cautiously.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-ci-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        Confidence intervals tell us how much to trust a sample estimate.
        A related question — one that comes up constantly in medicine,
        public health, and hiring — is how much to trust a test result.
        When a test comes back positive, what is the probability that the
        thing being tested for is actually there? Answering that question
        properly requires the tools of the next section.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-15-4-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Read a poll's margin of error</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a recent poll — from a news organization, a university
          research center, or a public opinion polling firm — and locate
          its reported margin of error and sample size. Compare the sample
          size to the rule-of-thumb list in this section. Then read the
          article accompanying the poll and note whether the authors
          correctly interpret the margin of error, or whether they treat
          the estimates as more certain than the data supports. Write a
          short paragraph reporting what you found.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  §15.5  Diagnostic Thresholds                                -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-sensitivity-specificity">
    <title>Diagnostic Thresholds</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Chapter 14 introduced Bayes' theorem, which lets us update
        probabilities when new evidence arrives. One of its most
        important applications is interpreting diagnostic tests: if a
        test comes back positive, what is the probability that the thing
        being tested for is actually present? The answer depends on how
        good the test is — which is where sensitivity and specificity
        come in.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-test-error">
      <title>Tests are not facts</title>
      <p>
        No diagnostic test is perfect. A strep test can come back
        positive when no strep is present (a <term>false positive</term>)
        or negative when strep is present (a <term>false negative</term>).
        A smoke detector can go off from burnt toast or fail to trigger
        in an actual fire. A spam filter can mark legitimate email as spam
        or let a phishing message through. In each case, the test has two
        distinct ways of being wrong, and the tradeoff between them turns
        out to be both fundamental and controllable.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-sensitivity">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>sensitivity</term> of a test is the probability
            that the test returns a positive result given that the
            condition is actually present.
            A highly sensitive test rarely misses cases that are there.
            A test with low sensitivity produces many false negatives.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch15-specificity">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>specificity</term> of a test is the probability
            that the test returns a negative result given that the
            condition is not present.
            A highly specific test rarely sounds false alarms. A test
            with low specificity produces many false positives.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-threshold-tradeoff">
      <title>The threshold tradeoff</title>
      <p>
        For many tests — especially those that measure a continuous
        variable such as a biomarker level, a credit score, or an image
        classification confidence — there is no single natural dividing
        line between <q>positive</q> and <q>negative.</q> A threshold
        has to be set somewhere. Move the threshold, and you change both
        sensitivity and specificity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sensitivity and specificity trade off against each other. Making
        a test more sensitive (catching more true cases) requires lowering
        the threshold, which also flags more people who do not have the
        condition — increasing the false-positive rate and decreasing
        specificity. Making a test more specific (fewer false alarms)
        requires raising the threshold, which lets more true cases slip
        through — increasing the false-negative rate and decreasing
        sensitivity.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tradeoff is not a defect in any particular test. It is a
        logical consequence of drawing a line through a continuous
        distribution of measurements.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-cholesterol-threshold">
        <title>Cholesterol testing and diagnostic thresholds</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the cholesterol example from
            <xref ref="sec-ch15-normal-distribution"/>. Serum cholesterol
            in the reference healthy population is normally distributed
            with mean 160 mg/dL and standard deviation 50 mg/dL. A
            clinical test currently flags anyone outside the 2-SD range
            (60 to 260 mg/dL) as abnormal. How would sensitivity and
            specificity change if the test instead flagged values outside
            the 3-SD range? Outside the 1-SD range?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            First, recall what the empirical rule says about the healthy
            reference population:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>Within 1 SD (110 to 210 mg/dL):
              approximately 68% of the healthy population.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>Within 2 SD (60 to 260 mg/dL):
              approximately 95% of the healthy population.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>Within 3 SD (10 to 310 mg/dL):
              approximately 99.7% of the healthy population.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            At the current threshold (2 SD), approximately 5% of healthy
            people have values outside 60 to 260 mg/dL and are flagged as
            abnormal — false positives. The test also has some sensitivity
            advantage: genuinely elevated cholesterol is more likely to
            fall outside this range.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Expanding to 3 SD.</alert> Flagging only values outside
            10 to 310 mg/dL means flagging just the 0.3% of healthy people at
            the extremes. Specificity increases (fewer healthy people are
            flagged), but sensitivity decreases: people with genuinely
            elevated cholesterol who still fall within 3 SD of the
            healthy-population mean will not be detected. Fewer false
            positives, but more false negatives.
          </p>
          <p>
            <alert>Narrowing to 1 SD.</alert> Flagging anyone outside
            110 to 210 mg/dL means flagging roughly 32% of the healthy
            population as abnormal. Sensitivity increases sharply — the
            test is very unlikely to miss anyone with a genuine problem
            — but specificity falls dramatically. Almost a third of
            healthy people now receive false positives, triggering
            unnecessary follow-up tests, patient anxiety, and wasted
            clinical resources.
          </p>
          <p>
            There is no universally correct threshold. The right choice
            depends on the stakes of each type of error. For a condition
            where missing a true case is catastrophic (a rare but
            treatable cancer), err toward higher sensitivity. For a
            condition where a false positive triggers a dangerous or
            expensive intervention, err toward higher specificity.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-bayes-bridge">
      <title>Connecting back to Bayes</title>
      <p>
        Sensitivity and specificity describe what a test does in the
        abstract. They do not tell you what a positive result means for
        any given patient. As Chapter 14 showed, that calculation requires
        one more ingredient: the base rate — the prior probability that
        the patient has the condition before the test is administered.
      </p>
      <p>
        A test with 90% sensitivity and 90% specificity sounds reliable.
        But if the condition affects only 1% of the population being
        screened (a low base rate), then — as the Bayes' theorem
        calculation from Chapter 14 showed — the majority of positive
        results will still be false positives. Sensitivity and specificity
        together with the base rate determine how much a positive result
        actually tells you.
      </p>
      <p>
        The practical upshot: a screening test applied to a low-risk
        population will produce many false positives even when the test
        is technically excellent. This is not a failure of the test — it
        is a consequence of the math. Understanding the tradeoff makes for
        both better medical decision-making and more skeptical reading of
        headlines about diagnostic breakthroughs.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-sensitivity-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        Sensitivity and specificity show one way statistical reasoning
        goes wrong in practice: technically correct numbers get applied
        without enough attention to what they actually mean. The closing
        section of this chapter is about that broader problem: how the
        same data can be made to look like almost anything, depending on
        how it is presented.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-15-5-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Find a screening scenario</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Identify a real-world screening or testing scenario — a medical
          test, a security screening protocol, a spam filter, a fraud
          detection algorithm, or anything analogous. Find or estimate
          the sensitivity and specificity. Then describe what happens to
          false positives and false negatives if the threshold is made
          more conservative (fewer flags overall). Write a short paragraph
          explaining the tradeoff and whether, in your view, the current
          threshold is set appropriately given the relative costs of each
          type of error.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  §15.6  Lying with Statistics                                 -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-lying-statistics">
    <title>Lying with Statistics</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Mark Twain popularized the observation — though he did not
        originate it — that there are three kinds of lies: lies, damned
        lies, and statistics. The quip exaggerates. Statistics, done
        carefully, are among the least deceptive tools we have for
        understanding large datasets. But statistics can be deployed
        deceptively, and they are, constantly. This section is about how.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-truncated-axes">
      <title>Truncated axes</title>
      <p>
        The most common visual distortion in data presentation is the
        truncated y-axis: a bar graph or line chart whose vertical axis
        does not begin at zero. Starting at zero is a convention that
        makes the height of each bar proportional to the value it
        represents. When the axis starts somewhere in the middle of the
        data range, small differences are made to look large.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-truncated-axis">
        <title>A truncated axis in political graphics</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            During a British election campaign, a graph circulated
            showing housing construction statistics for Labour- and
            Conservative-led governments. The y-axis began not at zero
            but far up the scale — near the minimum data value. The
            bar for Labour appeared to be roughly half the height of
            the Conservative bar, strongly suggesting that Conservative
            governments built twice as many homes.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="fig-ch15-truncated-axis-housing">
            <caption>A political housing graphic with a truncated y-axis.</caption>
            <image xml:id="image-ch15-truncated-axis-housing"
                   source="ch15-truncated-axis-housing.jpg"
                   width="70%">
              <description>
                <p>
                  A campaign-style bar graph titled <q>Number of new
                  homes is LOWER under Labour.</q> The vertical axis
                  jumps from 0 to 200,000 and then runs from 200,000 to
                  225,000. The 2023/24 Conservative bar reaches a little
                  above 220,000, while the 2024/25 Labour bar reaches
                  about 208,000. Because the visible scale begins near
                  200,000, the Labour bar appears much shorter than the
                  Conservative bar even though the numerical difference
                  is modest relative to the full scale.
                </p>
              </description>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <p>
            Reading the actual numbers on the axis revealed a gap of
            about 10% — not 100%. The visual impression of a two-to-one
            ratio was an artifact of the truncation. How would this
            graph look if the y-axis were redrawn starting at zero?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            With a y-axis starting at zero, the two bars would be nearly
            the same height. The genuine 10% difference would be visible
            but modest — because it is modest. The truncated axis
            converted a modest gap into an apparent chasm.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      <p>
        A truncated axis is not always dishonest. When differences between
        values are genuinely small and the story is precisely about those
        small differences, zooming in can be appropriate — as long as the
        truncation is clearly labeled and visually flagged. The problem
        arises when the truncation is invisible and used to make a minor
        difference look decisive.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-area-distortion">
      <title>Area and size distortions</title>
      <p>
        When data is represented by objects whose size varies — pictures,
        icons, bubbles, three-dimensional bars — the visual impression
        depends on how the scaling is done. Doubling a value should double
        the bar in a bar graph (one dimension). When a value is instead
        represented by a square, circle, or pictogram whose <em>height</em>
        doubles, the <em>area</em> of the image quadruples. The eye
        registers area and volume, not linear dimension alone.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-ch15-gas-price-cars">
        <title>The gas price illustration</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A data visualization shows the price of gasoline in two
            moments: <m>\$3.11</m> on January 20, 2025 and
            <m>\$4.51</m> on May 13, 2026. Each moment is represented
            by a picture of a truck, scaled to reflect the price. The
            later truck appears many times larger than the earlier truck
            — an impression far beyond what the price ratio warrants.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="fig-ch15-gas-price-car-size-distortion">
            <caption>A gas-price comparison distorted by changing the size of the truck image.</caption>
            <image xml:id="image-ch15-gas-price-car-size-distortion"
                   source="ch15-gas-price-car-size-distortion.png"
                   width="95%">
              <description>
                <p>
                  A whiteboard-style graphic titled <q>Gas Price
                  Increase Under Trump.</q> On the left, a small red
                  truck is labeled <q>Date: Jan 20, 2025</q> and
                  <q>Price: 3.11.</q> On the right, a much larger red
                  truck is labeled <q>Date: May 13, 2026</q> and
                  <q>Price: 4.51.</q> A vertical divider separates the
                  two trucks. The right truck's visual area is far more
                  than 45 percent larger, so the image exaggerates the
                  size of the price increase.
                </p>
              </description>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <p>
            The actual price ratio is <m>4.51 / 3.11 \approx 1.45</m>:
            the later price was about 45% higher. Why does a
            proportionally drawn truck look so much larger, and why is
            this misleading?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            When the later truck is drawn 1.45 times <em>taller</em> to
            represent a price 1.45 times higher, its width scales up
            proportionally too. The visible <em>area</em> of the image
            is therefore approximately <m>1.45 \times 1.45 \approx 2.1</m>
            times larger — and the impression of volume or
            three-dimensional size is larger still.
          </p>
          <p>
            A standard bar graph avoids this problem entirely: bars have
            a fixed width, so height alone carries the comparison, and a
            1.45× price difference produces a 1.45× bar. Pictograms and
            icon-based graphics invite area distortion unless the designer
            takes explicit care to scale by area rather than by height.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="fig-ch15-gas-price-bar-comparison">
            <caption>A clearer comparison keeps the visual scale tied to the vertical price axis.</caption>
            <image xml:id="image-ch15-gas-price-bar-comparison"
                   source="ch15-gas-price-bar-comparison.png"
                   width="95%">
              <description>
                <p>
                  A whiteboard-style graph titled <q>Gas Price Increase
                  Under Trump.</q> The y-axis runs from 0 dollars to
                  5 dollars in one-dollar increments. A smaller red
                  truck sits on a green rectangular bar labeled
                  <q>Date: Jan 20, 2025</q> and <q>Price: 3.11.</q>
                  A larger red truck sits on a taller green rectangular
                  bar labeled <q>Date: May 13, 2026</q> and
                  <q>Price: 4.51.</q> The comparison still shows an
                  increase, but the vertical axis makes the magnitude
                  easier to judge than the truck-size-only graphic.
                </p>
              </description>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </solution>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-cherry-picking">
      <title>Cherry-picking and baseline choices</title>
      <p>
        A third category of statistical distortion involves the choice of
        what to show and what to omit: the baseline year for a trend line,
        the subgroup highlighted in a summary, or the particular statistic
        selected to represent a more complex picture.
      </p>
      <p>
        A company reports revenue <q>up 150% from three years ago.</q>
        If three years ago was the company's worst year in a decade, a
        150% gain may represent a recovery to roughly where things were
        before — not a triumph. A trend line for crime that begins in
        1990 looks very different from one that starts in 1970, if there
        was a peak in 1980 and 2024 levels are still above those of
        1970 to 1975.
      </p>
      <p>
        A related distortion involves the choice between relative and
        absolute measures. A clinical trial finds that a new drug reduces
        the <em>relative</em> risk of some outcome by 50%. This sounds
        large. If the absolute risk without the drug is 2% and with the
        drug is 1%, the absolute risk reduction is 1 percentage point —
        which may or may not justify the drug's cost and side effects.
        Both the relative and the absolute figures are numerically correct;
        they describe different things. The relative reduction is almost
        always the larger number, and it is almost always the one the
        press release leads with.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-honest-graph">
      <title>What an honest graph does</title>
      <p>
        Negative examples are useful, but the goal is not just to avoid
        bad graphs — it is to recognize what good ones look like. An
        honest data visualization:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>uses a zero baseline, or makes any truncation obvious with
          a clear break in the axis;</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>uses area and size consistently with the data (constant bar
          width; pictograms sized by area, not height);</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>chooses baselines and time ranges that represent the full
          relevant context, not just the most flattering window;</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>reports both relative and absolute changes when the
          distinction matters;</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>includes sample sizes and margins of error when the data
          comes from a survey or study.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Statistical literacy is not primarily the ability to compute
        standard deviations by hand. It is the habit of asking, when
        confronted with a graph or a statistic: <em>What comparison is
        this actually making? What would the same data look like presented
        differently? What is not being shown?</em>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-15-6-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Find a misleading visualization</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a graph or chart from a news source, social media, a
          corporate report, or a political communication from the past
          year that uses at least one of the distortions discussed in
          this section — truncated axes, area or size distortion,
          cherry-picked baselines, or a choice of statistic that obscures
          more than it reveals. Describe the distortion precisely: what
          does the visualization suggest, and what would a reader conclude
          if the same data were presented honestly? If possible, sketch
          or describe an alternative representation that would present
          the data more accurately.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  CHAPTER CONCLUSION: Summary                                 -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <conclusion xml:id="ch-statistical-reasoning-conclusion">

    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch15-summary">
      <title>Summary by section</title>
      <p>
        <alert>Measuring the Middle (§15.1).</alert> A dataset's center
        can be described by the mean (arithmetic average), the median
        (middle value when ordered), or the mode (most frequent value).
        The three measures agree when data is symmetric and diverge when
        it is skewed or contains extreme values. The mean is sensitive to
        outliers; the median is resistant to them. For skewed distributions
        — income, home prices, hospital costs — the median is typically
        the more informative description of what is typical.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Measuring Spread (§15.2).</alert> The range (maximum minus
        minimum) is the simplest measure of spread but the least stable.
        The standard deviation measures how far, on average, values sit
        from the mean. For a sample, it is computed in six steps: find the
        mean, subtract it from each value, square the differences, add
        them up, divide using the sample-data correction, and take the
        square root. A
        large standard deviation means the data is spread out; a small
        one means it clusters tightly around the mean.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>The Normal Distribution (§15.3).</alert> Many natural and
        social datasets are approximately normally distributed — bell-shaped,
        symmetric, thinning symmetrically on both sides. The empirical
        rule states that in any approximately normal distribution, 68% of
        values fall within 1 SD of the mean, 95% within 2 SD, and 99.7%
        within 3 SD. Two numbers — the mean and the standard deviation —
        together characterize the entire distribution when the data is
        approximately normal.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Confidence Intervals and Margin of Error (§15.4).</alert>
        A sample gives an estimate of a population value, but any estimate
        from a sample carries uncertainty. A 95% confidence interval is a
        range of values that, if the sampling procedure were repeated many
        times, would contain the true population value in approximately
        95% of repetitions. Larger random samples have smaller margins of
        error, but the improvement slows down: a sample of 500 gives a
        margin of error of about plus or minus 4.4%, while a sample of
        1,000 gives about plus or minus 3.1%. A four-point lead in a poll
        with a four-point margin of error is not a lead.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Diagnostic Thresholds (§15.5).</alert> Sensitivity is the
        probability that a test returns positive given that the condition
        is present; specificity is the probability that it returns negative
        given that the condition is absent. For tests measuring a continuous variable,
        the positive/negative threshold is a choice — and moving it
        trades sensitivity against specificity. Combined with the base
        rate from Chapter 14's Bayes' theorem, these two quantities
        determine how much a positive result actually tells you.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Lying with Statistics (§15.6).</alert> Common forms of
        statistical distortion include truncated axes (which make small
        differences look large), area and size distortions (which
        misrepresent ratios by scaling two- or three-dimensional objects),
        and cherry-picked baselines or statistics (which present the most
        favorable slice of a more complex picture). Statistical literacy
        requires asking what an honest presentation of the same data would
        look like.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </conclusion>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  KEY TERMS                                                    -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section xml:id="sec-ch15-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-bimodal">
        <title>Bimodal</title>
        <p>A dataset with two distinct modes — two values (or ranges)
        each appearing more often than others, producing two peaks in
        the distribution. (§15.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-confidence-interval">
        <title>Confidence interval</title>
        <p>A range of values computed from a sample such that, if the
        same sampling procedure were repeated many times, approximately
        the stated percentage of intervals would contain the true
        population value. (§15.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-confidence-level">
        <title>Confidence level</title>
        <p>The percentage of confidence intervals, generated by the
        same procedure applied repeatedly, that would capture the true
        population value. Commonly 95%. (§15.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-empirical-rule">
        <title>Empirical rule</title>
        <p>In an approximately normal distribution: approximately 68%
        of values fall within 1 SD of the mean, 95% within 2 SD, and
        99.7% within 3 SD. Also called the 68-95-99.7 rule. (§15.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-false-negative">
        <title>False negative</title>
        <p>A test result that is negative when the condition is actually
        present. (§15.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-false-positive">
        <title>False positive</title>
        <p>A test result that is positive when the condition is actually
        absent. (§15.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-margin-of-error">
        <title>Margin of error</title>
        <p>Half the width of a confidence interval — the amount added
        to and subtracted from a sample estimate to form the interval.
        In public-opinion polling, a random sample of 500 has a margin
        of error of about plus or minus 4.4% at the 95% confidence level; a random
        sample of 1,000 has a margin of error of about plus or minus 3.1%. (§15.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-mean">
        <title>Mean</title>
        <p>The arithmetic average of a dataset: the sum of all values
        divided by the number of values. (§15.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-median">
        <title>Median</title>
        <p>The middle value of a dataset arranged in ascending order;
        the average of the two middle values for an even-numbered
        dataset. (§15.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-mode">
        <title>Mode</title>
        <p>The value (or values) that appears most often in a dataset.
        (§15.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-normal-distribution">
        <title>Normal distribution</title>
        <p>A symmetric, bell-shaped distribution in which values cluster
        around the mean and decrease in frequency as they move farther
        from the mean in either direction. Characterized entirely by its
        mean and standard deviation. (§15.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-range">
        <title>Range</title>
        <p>The simplest measure of spread: the difference between the
        maximum and minimum values in a dataset. (§15.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-sensitivity">
        <title>Sensitivity</title>
        <p>The probability that a test returns positive given that the
        condition is present. (§15.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-specificity">
        <title>Specificity</title>
        <p>The probability that a test returns negative given that the
        condition is absent. (§15.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-standard-deviation">
        <title>Standard deviation</title>
        <p>A measure of spread: the square root of the average squared
        deviation from the mean. Expressed in the same units as the
        original data. (§15.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-unimodal">
        <title>Unimodal</title>
        <p>A dataset with a single mode — one value that appears more
        often than any other. (§15.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch15-variance">
        <title>Variance</title>
        <p>The average of the squared deviations from the mean; the
        square of the standard deviation. Expressed in squared units of
        the original data. (§15.2)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!--  END-OF-CHAPTER EXERCISES                                    -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch15">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Exercises are organized by section. Unless otherwise noted, show
        all work. Selected solutions appear in the back matter; full
        solutions are available in the instructor's manual.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <!-- Exercise Set 1: Measuring the Middle -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Measuring the Middle</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each dataset below, find the mean, median, and mode
          (if one exists). Then answer the interpretation question.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A professor records quiz scores for ten students: 62, 74,
            74, 78, 80, 83, 83, 83, 91, 100. Find the mean, median, and
            mode. Which measure would you cite if you wanted to argue the
            class performed well? Which would you cite if you wanted to
            argue that many students struggled?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Home sale prices (in thousands of dollars) in a neighborhood
            during one month: 185, 190, 205, 210, 215, 220, 225, 230,
            240, 1150. Find the mean and median. Which better represents
            a typical home price here, and why?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A shoe store tracks women's sizes sold over a month:
            6, 6.5, 7, 7, 7.5, 7.5, 8, 8, 8, 8.5, 9, 10. Explain why
            the mode is the most useful of the three measures here. What
            is the mode?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The incomes of a ten-person workplace are:
            <m>\$32{,}000</m>, <m>\$35{,}000</m>, <m>\$38{,}000</m>,
            <m>\$41{,}000</m>, <m>\$45{,}000</m>, <m>\$48{,}000</m>,
            <m>\$52{,}000</m>, <m>\$55{,}000</m>, <m>\$60{,}000</m>,
            <m>\$890{,}000</m>. The CEO uses the mean income in a press
            release to describe the company as a great place to work. An
            employee uses the median income in a complaint to a journalist.
            Compute both numbers. Which characterization is more
            informative, and why?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Hours per week twelve students report studying: 2, 3, 5, 5,
            6, 8, 8, 10, 10, 12, 15, 40. Is this distribution
            approximately symmetric or skewed? Which measure of center
            is most appropriate to report? Compute that measure.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s01-06">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A dataset of six values has a mean of 20, a median of 18, and
            a mode of 15. Without knowing the exact values, what does the
            relationship between mean and median suggest about the shape
            of the distribution?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <!-- Exercise Set 2: Standard Deviation -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Standard Deviation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For problems that ask you to compute the standard deviation,
          show all six steps. Round to two decimal places.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute the sample standard deviation of these five exam
            scores: 70, 75, 80, 85, 90.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute the sample standard deviation of these five exam
            scores: 30, 60, 80, 90, 100.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two sections of the same course have identical class means
            of 78. Section A has a standard deviation of 4; Section B
            has a standard deviation of 22. Describe, without further
            calculation, what these two standard deviations imply about
            the distribution of scores in each section.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A quality-control process measures bolt diameters (in mm).
            Ten measurements: 9.98, 10.01, 10.02, 9.99, 10.00, 10.03,
            9.97, 10.01, 10.00, 9.99. Compute the sample standard
            deviation. The acceptable range is 10.00 mm, plus or minus
            0.10 mm.
            Based on the standard deviation, does the process appear to
            be under control?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s02-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A dataset has mean 50 and standard deviation 10. A value of
            75 appears in the dataset. How many standard deviations above
            the mean is this value? If the data is approximately normally
            distributed, is this value unusual? Explain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <!-- Exercise Set 3: The Normal Distribution -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: The Normal Distribution</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the empirical rule (68-95-99.7) to answer the questions
          below. Assume all distributions are approximately normal.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The heights of adult women in a city are normally distributed
            with mean 165 cm and standard deviation 6 cm. What percentage
            of women have heights between 159 and 171 cm? Between 153 and
            177 cm?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A factory produces light bulbs with mean lifetime 1,000 hours
            and standard deviation 50 hours. Out of a batch of 10,000
            bulbs, approximately how many would you expect to last more
            than 1,100 hours?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the pine tree example from §15.3: mean diameter
            150 cm, standard deviation 30 cm, 500 trees. Approximately
            how many trees have a diameter greater than 210 cm?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A standardized test is normally distributed with mean 500 and
            standard deviation 100. (a) What score marks the boundary of
            the top 16% of test-takers? (b) What score marks the boundary
            of the bottom 2.5%? (c) Between what two scores do the middle
            99.7% of test-takers fall?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s03-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A news article reports that annual rainfall in a certain city
            is normally distributed with mean 40 inches and standard
            deviation 5 inches, and describes a year with 55 inches of
            rainfall as <q>extraordinary.</q> Using the empirical rule,
            is this description warranted? How many standard deviations
            from the mean is 55 inches?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <!-- Exercise Set 4: Confidence Intervals -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Confidence Intervals and Margin of Error</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the rule-of-thumb approximations from §15.4. At the 95%
          confidence level, samples of 400, 500, 600, 1,000, 1,500, and
          2,000 have margins of error of about plus or minus 4.9%,
          plus or minus 4.4%, plus or minus 4.1%, plus or minus 3.1%,
          plus or minus 2.5%, and plus or minus 2.2%, respectively.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A poll of 1,000 randomly selected adults finds that 58%
            support a proposed ballot measure. Use the rule-of-thumb
            margin of error to state the confidence interval for the true
            proportion of supporters. Does the result support the claim
            that a majority favors the measure? Explain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A poll of 400 voters finds that Candidate X leads Candidate Y
            by 6 percentage points (53% to 47%). A headline says:
            <q>Candidate X has a commanding lead.</q> Is this
            characterization supported by the data? Use the rule-of-thumb
            margin of error and explain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A campus survey of 500 students finds that 61% support
            extending library hours during finals. A student newspaper
            reports: <q>Students overwhelmingly support longer library
            hours.</q> Use the rule-of-thumb margin of error for a sample
            of 500. What confidence interval should the article have in
            mind, and does the headline overstate the result?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A news article about a clinical trial reports: <q>The
            treatment was effective in 62% of patients (95% CI:
            55% to 69%).</q> (a) What is the margin of error implied by
            this interval? (b) Does this confidence interval support the
            claim that the treatment is effective in more than half of all
            patients? Explain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s04-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in plain language the difference between these two
            statements: (a) <q>There is a 95% probability that the true
            proportion lies in this interval.</q> (b) <q>If we repeated
            this sampling procedure many times, approximately 95% of the
            resulting intervals would contain the true proportion.</q>
            Which statement correctly describes what a 95% confidence
            interval means?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <!-- Exercise Set 5: Diagnostic Thresholds -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Diagnostic Thresholds</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each problem, identify the relevant quantities and answer
          the question. Where asked, explain what happens to false
          positives and false negatives when the threshold shifts.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A test for a rare condition has sensitivity of 95% and
            specificity of 90%. (a) What is the false-negative rate?
            (b) What is the false-positive rate? (c) If missing a true
            case is catastrophic, which do you prioritize: high
            sensitivity or high specificity? Why?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the cholesterol example from §15.5: normally
            distributed with mean 160 mg/dL, standard deviation 50 mg/dL.
            The current test flags anyone outside the 2-SD range
            (60 to 260 mg/dL). (a) What percentage of the healthy population
            is currently flagged as abnormal? (b) If the threshold is
            moved to 1.5 SDs from the mean, what are the new upper and
            lower cutoffs? (c) Would this change increase or decrease
            sensitivity? Increase or decrease specificity?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A university plagiarism-detection tool flags 8% of submitted
            papers as likely plagiarized. On review, 3 out of every 4
            flagged papers turn out to be legitimate work. The remaining
            1 in 4 are genuine cases of plagiarism. Estimate the tool's
            false-positive rate as a percentage of all papers submitted,
            and comment on whether this seems like an acceptable tradeoff.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s05-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A spam filter is set to be highly sensitive: it catches 99%
            of spam but also marks 15% of legitimate email as spam. A
            colleague argues this is fine because 99% sensitivity is
            excellent. What is missing from this analysis? What
            additional information would you need to evaluate whether
            the filter's threshold is set correctly?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <!-- Exercise Set 6: Lying with Statistics -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Lying with Statistics</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each item, identify the statistical distortion present
          and explain how the presentation would change if the data were
          presented honestly.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A bar graph shows monthly sales for two competing products.
            Product A's bar is roughly twice the height of Product B's.
            The y-axis begins at <m>\$980{,}000</m> and ends at
            <m>\$1{,}050{,}000</m>. Product A's sales are
            <m>\$1{,}040{,}000</m>; Product B's are
            <m>\$1{,}010{,}000</m>. What is the actual percentage
            difference in sales? What would the graph look like if the
            y-axis began at zero?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An infographic shows national debt over time as a stack of
            coins, with each coin representing one year's debt level.
            The coins for the most recent three years are both larger in
            diameter and taller than earlier coins, to represent higher
            debt levels. Describe two ways this visualization
            misrepresents the data.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s06-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A pharmaceutical company reports that a new drug reduces the
            relative risk of heart attack by 33%. The fine print reveals
            that the control group had a 3% annual heart attack rate and
            the treatment group had a 2% rate. (a) What is the absolute
            risk reduction? (b) What does <q>33% relative risk
            reduction</q> mean here? (c) Which statistic is more
            informative for a patient deciding whether to take the drug,
            and why?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s06-04">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A city government presents a graph showing crime rates from
            2015 to 2024, with a sharp downward trend. A community
            organizer notes that 2015 was a local peak in crime and that
            extending the graph back to 2005 would show 2024 rates are
            still higher than those of 2005 to 2010. What type of distortion
            is this, and what principle does it violate?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-s06-05">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two news organizations report on the same study about a new
            nutritional supplement. Organization A says: <q>Supplement
            users were 40% less likely to develop the condition.</q>
            Organization B says: <q>The supplement reduced risk by 2
            percentage points — from 5% to 3%.</q> Both statements are
            numerically accurate. Explain what each is measuring, which
            is more informative for a general audience, and why the two
            framings might lead to different decisions.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <!-- Writing Prompt -->

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch15-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use §15.6 with the reconstruction skills from Part I.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch15-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a recent news article, advertisement, or public
            statement — political, corporate, or public-health — that
            uses at least one statistic as evidence for a claim. In
            approximately 300 words: (1) identify the claim being made
            and the statistic offered in support of it; (2) identify any
            distortion in how the statistic is presented — or, if the
            presentation is honest, explain what makes it honest; and
            (3) explain whether the statistic, presented accurately,
            would still support the claim.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
